# GNN Protein Thermostability Predictor

A Graph Neural Network that predicts protein thermostability (B-factor)
from 3D molecular structure graphs. Built as part of an NSF ACCESS
allocation preparation portfolio.

---

## Architecture

Each protein structure is converted into a graph:
- **Nodes** — residues with 23-dim features (one-hot residue type, B-factor, sequence position, chain ID)
- **Edges** — pairs of residues within 8Å in 3D space
- **Target** — mean crystallographic B-factor (proxy for thermostability)
```
Node features (23-dim)
      │
GCNConv(23 → 64) + ReLU
      │
GCNConv(64 → 64) + ReLU
      │
Global Mean Pooling
      │
Linear(64 → 32) + ReLU
      │
Linear(32 → 1) → predicted B-factor
```

## Results

| Model    | MAE    | R²     |
|----------|--------|--------|
| Baseline | 12.154 | 0.000  |
| GCN      | 0.350  | 0.997  |
| GAT      | 1.614  | 0.966  |

See [RESULTS.md](RESULTS.md) for full analysis.

## Setup
```bash
python -m venv venv
venv\Scripts\activate
pip install torch torch_geometric biopython pandas loguru matplotlib scikit-learn networkx tqdm
```

## Usage
```bash
# Fetch dataset (97 protein structures)
python get_data.py

# Train GCN and GAT models
python src/train.py

# Run inference on new structures
python src/inference.py
```

## Project Structure
```
gnn-protein-thermostability/
├── src/
│   ├── graph_builder.py   # PDB → PyG graph conversion
│   ├── model.py           # GCNConv and GATConv architectures
│   ├── train.py           # Training loop, evaluation, loss curves
│   └── inference.py       # End-to-end prediction from PDB ID
├── output/
│   ├── model_gcn.pt
│   ├── model_gat.pt
│   ├── loss_curve_gcn.png
│   └── loss_curve_gat.png
├── get_data.py
├── RESULTS.md
└── README.md
```

## Connection to Project 1

The dataset used here was generated by the
[PDB Parallel Data Pipeline](https://github.com/Cebred25-cloud/pdb-pipeline)
— a Dask-based parallel ingestion pipeline that achieved 6-12x speedup
over serial processing. This GNN motivates the need for GPU compute hours
on an ACCESS cluster to scale to the full PDB (~200k structures).

## Next Steps

Scale to the full PDB using ACCESS HPC GPU resources. The current model
trains in minutes on 97 structures — scaling to 200k structures requires
distributed GPU training, which is the direct motivation for this
ACCESS allocation request.